<typeStatus id="592E887DFFF16345C0A26C4EB3C8D2D7" box="[151,207,362,385]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">Type</typeStatus>
species (by monotypy) 
<taxonomicName id="41954D5CFFF16345C1D46C4EB0F0D2D7" authority="White, 1841" authorityName="White" authorityYear="1841" box="[481,1015,362,385]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Linyphia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argyrobapta" subGenus="Leucauge">
<emphasis id="B4E1EACDFFF16345C1D46C4EB066D2D7" box="[481,865,362,385]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">Linyphia (Leucauge) argyrobapta</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="E2044B2EFFF16345C35D6C4EB0F0D2D7" author="White" box="[872,1015,362,385]" pageId="5" pageNumber="36" refString="White, A. (1841) Description of new or little known Arachnida. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, 7, 471 - 477." type="journal article" year="1841">
White, 
<number id="305D24F8FFF16345C3896C4EB0F0D2D7" box="[956,1015,362,385]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" value="1841.0">1841</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="41954D5CFFF16345C4C76C4EB252D2F7" authority="Walckenaer, 1841" authorityName="Walckenaer" authorityYear="1841" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Epeira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="venusta">
<emphasis id="B4E1EACDFFF16345C4C76C4EB69BD2D7" box="[1266,1436,362,385]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">Epeira venusta</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="E2044B2EFFF16345C0A26CAEB252D2F7" author="Walckenaer" box="[151,341,394,417]" pageId="5" pageNumber="36" refString="Walckenaer, C. A. (1841) Histoire naturelle des Insects. Apteres. Paris 2, 1 - 549." type="journal article" year="1841">
Walckenaer, 
<number id="305D24F8FFF16345C1156CAEB252D2F7" box="[288,341,394,417]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" value="1841.0">1841</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="862A36DFFFF16345C0A26CF4B1F3D10C" blockId="5.[151,1437,464,602]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">
In his field notes Darwin suggested the new genus name 
<taxonomicName id="41954D5CFFF16345C3746CF4B0B3D2BF" box="[833,948,464,489]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" genus="Leucauge" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B4E1EACDFFF16345C3746CF4B0B3D2BF" box="[833,948,464,489]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">Leucauge</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for 
<taxonomicName id="41954D5CFFF16345C3D26CF4B77ED2BF" box="[999,1145,464,489]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Linyphia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argyrobapta">
<emphasis id="B4E1EACDFFF16345C3D26CF4B77ED2BF" box="[999,1145,464,489]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">argyrobapta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation id="E2044B2EFFF16345C48C6CF4B666D2BC" author="Keynes" box="[1209,1377,464,490]" pageId="5" pageNumber="35" refString="Keynes, R. ed. (2000) Charles Darwin's zoology notes &amp; specimen lists from H. M. S. Beagle. Cambridge, Cambridge University Press, UK, 464 pp." type="book" year="2000">
Keynes, 
<number id="305D24F8FFF16345C5146CF4B666D2BC" box="[1313,1377,464,490]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" value="2000.0">2000</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), but nevertheless 
<bibRefCitation id="E2044B2EFFF16345C1086CD1B2E1D159" author="White" box="[317,486,501,527]" pageId="5" pageNumber="36" refString="White, A. (1841) Description of new or little known Arachnida. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, 7, 471 - 477." type="journal article" year="1841">
White (
<number id="305D24F8FFF16345C1A96CD1B2DAD159" box="[412,477,501,527]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" value="1841.0">1841</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName id="41954D5CFFF16345C2476CD1B00AD158" box="[626,781,501,526]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Linyphia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argyrobapta">
<emphasis id="B4E1EACDFFF16345C2476CD1B00AD158" box="[626,781,501,526]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">argyrobapta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a species of 
<taxonomicName id="41954D5CFFF16345C3EC6CD1B74ED158" box="[985,1097,501,526]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Linyphia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B4E1EACDFFF16345C3EC6CD1B74ED158" box="[985,1097,501,526]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">Linyphia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and treated 
<taxonomicName id="41954D5CFFF16345C4DD6CD1B665D158" box="[1256,1378,501,526]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" genus="Leucauge" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B4E1EACDFFF16345C4DD6CD1B665D158" box="[1256,1378,501,526]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">Leucauge</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a subgenus, not as a new genus. This should be hardly surprising given that in his paper 
<bibRefCitation id="E2044B2EFFF16345C48E6F3EB69BD162" author="White" box="[1211,1436,538,564]" pageId="5" pageNumber="36" refString="White, A. (1841) Description of new or little known Arachnida. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, 7, 471 - 477." type="journal article" year="1841">
White (
<number id="305D24F8FFF16345C5226F3EB65ED162" box="[1303,1369,538,564]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" value="1841.0">1841</number>
: 
<number id="305D24F8FFF16345C5506F3EB694D162" box="[1381,1427,538,564]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" value="471.0">471</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
explicitly expressed reluctance to erect new genera:
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="862A36DFFFF16345C0F36FAEB65AD045" blockId="5.[188,1398,650,787]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis id="B4E1EACDFFF16345C0F36FAEB277D1B8" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">“I describe them without any systematic order, but having necessarily numbered each species, intend afterwards giving a classified index: the descriptions are in many instances prolix, and I have in most cases given the</emphasis>
generic 
<emphasis id="B4E1EACDFFF16345C1E36FF1B65AD045" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">character of each species. I have done this because, at present, I am unwilling to propose new names if I can possibly refer the species I describe to any of ties established genera.”</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="862A36DFFFF16345C0F16E61B044D732" blockId="5.[151,1437,837,1124]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">
There is no hint in Darwin’s field book suggesting that 
<taxonomicName id="41954D5CFFF16345C3676E61B0E5D008" box="[850,994,837,862]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Linyphia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argyrobapta">
<emphasis id="B4E1EACDFFF16345C3676E61B0E5D008" box="[850,994,837,862]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">argyrobapta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
had close affinities with 
<taxonomicName id="41954D5CFFF16345C5396E61B673D008" box="[1292,1396,837,862]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Linyphia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B4E1EACDFFF16345C5396E61B673D008" box="[1292,1396,837,862]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">Linyphia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In fact, Darwin’s entry (page 
<number id="305D24F8FFF16345C1EB6E4EB2FBD0D2" box="[478,508,874,900]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" value="38.0">38</number>
of this particular field book, as transcribed in 
<bibRefCitation id="E2044B2EFFF16345C4036E4EB7E7D0D2" author="Keynes" box="[1078,1248,874,900]" pageId="5" pageNumber="35" refString="Keynes, R. ed. (2000) Charles Darwin's zoology notes &amp; specimen lists from H. M. S. Beagle. Cambridge, Cambridge University Press, UK, 464 pp." type="book" year="2000">
Keynes, 
<number id="305D24F8FFF16345C4946E4EB7E7D0D2" box="[1185,1248,874,900]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" value="2000.0">2000</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) starts with the following text: “Spider, orbilates [orbitéles]; closely allied to 
<taxonomicName id="41954D5CFFF16345C34D6EB4B0C2D0FC" authority="Walckenaer, 1805" authorityName="Walckenaer" authorityYear="1805" box="[888,965,912,938]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Epeira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Epeira</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="41954D5CFFF16345C3E36EB4B748D0FC" box="[982,1103,912,938]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" genus="Leucauge" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Leucauge</taxonomicName>
. 
<emphasis id="B4E1EACDFFF16345C46F6EB4B7A9D0FF" box="[1114,1198,912,937]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">[illeg.]</emphasis>
)”. Thus the generic placement in 
<taxonomicName id="41954D5CFFF16345C1776E91B2B6D098" box="[322,433,949,974]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Linyphia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B4E1EACDFFF16345C1776E91B2B6D098" box="[322,433,949,974]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">Linyphia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
must be entirely attributed to White. Although Waterhouse’s (
<number id="305D24F8FFF16345C4F96E91B617D099" box="[1228,1296,949,975]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" value="1902.0">1902</number>
: 
<number id="305D24F8FFF16345C5216E91B642D099" box="[1300,1349,949,975]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" value="198.0">198</number>
) 
<emphasis id="B4E1EACDFFF16345C5626E91B21DD0A5" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">Index Zoologicus</emphasis>
provides the first use of 
<taxonomicName id="41954D5CFFF16345C20A6EFEB1B6D0A5" box="[575,689,986,1011]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" genus="Leucauge" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B4E1EACDFFF16345C20A6EFEB1B6D0A5" box="[575,689,986,1011]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">Leucauge</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a genus name, the first arachnologists to use Darwin’s name at the genus rank were F. O. P.- 
<bibRefCitation id="E2044B2EFFF16345C23B6924B1F3D74C" author="Cambridge" box="[526,756,1024,1050]" pageId="5" pageNumber="34" refString="Cambridge, F. O. P. -. (1902 a) Arachnida - Araneida and Opiliones. In Biologia Centrali-Americana, Zoology. London, 2, 313 - 424." type="journal article" year="1902" yearSuffix="a">
Cambridge (
<number id="305D24F8FFF16345C2926924B1E1D74C" box="[679,742,1024,1050]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" value="1902.0">1902</number>
a
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="E2044B2EFFF16345C3346924B039D74C" author="Cambridge" box="[769,830,1024,1050]" pageId="5" pageNumber="34" refString="Cambridge, F. O. P. -. (1903) Arachnida - Araneida and Opiliones. In Biologia Centrali-Americana, Zoology. London, 2, 425 - 464." type="journal article" year="1903">
<number id="305D24F8FFF16345C3346924B039D74C" box="[769,830,1024,1050]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" value="1903.0">1903</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<bibRefCitation id="E2044B2EFFF16345C3B76924B749D74C" author="Simon" box="[898,1102,1024,1050]" pageId="5" pageNumber="36" refString="Simon, E. (1903) Arachnides de la Guinee espagnole. Memorias de la Real Sociedad Espanola de historia natural 1 (3), 65 - 124." type="journal article" year="1903">
E. Simon (
<number id="305D24F8FFF16345C4316924B742D74C" box="[1028,1093,1024,1050]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" value="1903.0">1903</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. In one of his papers on the 
<typeStatus id="592E887DFFF16345C0A26901B3CDD769" box="[151,202,1061,1087]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">type</typeStatus>
species of the genera of 
<taxonomicName id="41954D5CFFF16345C1C76901B07ED769" authority="Cambridge (1902b: 16)" authorityName="Cambridge" authorityPageNumber="16" authorityYear="1902" box="[498,889,1061,1087]" class="Arachnida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">
Araneae, 
<bibRefCitation id="E2044B2EFFF16345C2566901B07ED769" author="Cambridge" box="[611,889,1061,1087]" pageId="5" pageNumber="34" refString="Cambridge, F. O. P. -. (1902 b) A revision of the genera of Araneae or spiders with reference to their type species. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, (7) 9, 5 - 20." type="journal article" year="1902" yearSuffix="b">
Cambridge (
<number id="305D24F8FFF16345C2C26901B031D769" box="[759,822,1061,1087]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" value="1902.0">1902</number>
b: 
<number id="305D24F8FFF16345C3676901B077D769" box="[850,880,1061,1087]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" value="16.0">16</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
explicitly discusses the rank of 
<taxonomicName id="41954D5CFFF16345C4C26901B66ED768" box="[1271,1385,1061,1086]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" genus="Leucauge" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B4E1EACDFFF16345C4C26901B66ED768" box="[1271,1385,1061,1086]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">Leucauge</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and quite openly expresses his dislike for Darwin’s new name:
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="862A36DFFFF16345C0F369B1B014D782" blockId="5.[188,1398,1173,1310]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis id="B4E1EACDFFF16345C0F369B1B295D782" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">“No one that has ever been in a tropical Brazilian forest will hesitate one moment in recognizing this as a species of the</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="41954D5CFFF16345C1AC699EB132D782" box="[409,565,1210,1236]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" genus="Argyroepeira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Argyroepeira</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B4E1EACDFFF16345C209699FB014D782" box="[572,787,1211,1236]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">group of Emerton.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CE8F6554FFF16345C0F369C4B75BD6A9" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" type="description">
<paragraph id="862A36DFFFF16345C0F369C4B1B9D648" blockId="5.[188,1398,1173,1310]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis id="B4E1EACDFFF16345C0F369C4B78ED7AF" box="[198,1161,1248,1273]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">One feels sorry at the necessity of sacrificing so beautiful a name for the ugly one</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="41954D5CFFF16345C4A469C4B604D7AC" box="[1169,1283,1248,1274]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" genus="Leucauge" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Leucauge</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B4E1EACDFFF16345C53F69C4B1B9D648" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">proposed by Darwin, but priority lies with the latter.”</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="862A36DFFFF16345C0F16874B75BD6A9" blockId="5.[151,1436,1360,1535]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">
<bibRefCitation id="E2044B2EFFF16345C0F16874B2C3D63C" author="Cameron" box="[196,452,1360,1386]" pageId="5" pageNumber="34" refString="Cameron, H. D. (2005) An etymological dictionary of North American spider genus names. In: Spiders of North America: an identification manua l. (Eds. D. Ubick et al.). American Arachnological Society, USA, 377 pp." type="book" year="2005">
<collectingCountry id="FE82764FFFF16345C0F16874B234D63C" box="[196,307,1360,1386]" name="Cameroon" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">Cameron</collectingCountry>
(
<number id="305D24F8FFF16345C1716874B282D63C" box="[324,389,1360,1386]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" value="2005.0">2005</number>
: 
<number id="305D24F8FFF16345C1BF6874B2BCD63C" box="[394,443,1360,1386]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" value="302.0">302</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
deciphered the etymology of 
<taxonomicName id="41954D5CFFF16345C3006874B0ACD63F" box="[821,939,1360,1385]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" genus="Leucauge" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B4E1EACDFFF16345C3006874B0ACD63F" box="[821,939,1360,1385]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">Leucauge</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(which means “with a bright gleam”, in reference to the characteristic silvery guanine abdominal marks) and pointed out how 
<bibRefCitation id="E2044B2EFFF16345C4876851B664D6D9" author="Bonnet" box="[1202,1379,1397,1423]" pageId="5" pageNumber="34" refString="Bonnet, P. (1957) Bibliographia Araneorum. Analyse methodique de toute la literature araneologique jusqu'en 1939. Tome II, 3 e partie: G-M. Toulouse, Les Artisans de l'Imprimerie Douladoure, 1927 - 3026 pp." type="journal article" year="1957">
Bonnet (
<number id="305D24F8FFF16345C52E6851B65DD6D9" box="[1307,1370,1397,1423]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" value="1957.0">1957</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
also grumbled about the replacement of the more recent genus name 
<taxonomicName id="41954D5CFFF16345C3B268BFB7DFD6E2" authority="Emerton, 1884" authorityName="Emerton" authorityYear="1884" box="[903,1240,1434,1460]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" genus="Argyroepeira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B4E1EACDFFF16345C3B268BFB724D6E2" box="[903,1059,1435,1460]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">Argyroepeira</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="E2044B2EFFF16345C41F68BEB7DFD6E2" author="Emerton" box="[1066,1240,1434,1460]" pageId="5" pageNumber="35" refString="Emerton, J. H. (1884) New England spiders of the family Epeiridae. Transactions of the Connecticut Academy of Arts and Sciences, 6, 295 - 342." type="journal article" year="1884">
Emerton, 
<number id="305D24F8FFF16345C4A868BEB7DFD6E2" box="[1181,1240,1434,1460]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" value="1884.0">1884</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
by the older one 
<taxonomicName id="41954D5CFFF16345C0A268E4B20ED68F" box="[151,265,1472,1497]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" genus="Leucauge" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B4E1EACDFFF16345C0A268E4B20ED68F" box="[151,265,1472,1497]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">Leucauge</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
after having been forgotten for sixty years. We join Professor 
<bibRefCitation id="E2044B2EFFF16345C3D968E4B7E6D68C" author="Cameron" box="[1004,1249,1472,1498]" pageId="5" pageNumber="34" refString="Cameron, H. D. (2005) An etymological dictionary of North American spider genus names. In: Spiders of North America: an identification manua l. (Eds. D. Ubick et al.). American Arachnological Society, USA, 377 pp." type="book" year="2005">
<collectingCountry id="FE82764FFFF16345C3D968E4B750D68C" box="[1004,1111,1472,1498]" name="Cameroon" pageId="5" pageNumber="24">Cameron</collectingCountry>
(
<number id="305D24F8FFF16345C45268E4B7A1D68C" box="[1127,1190,1472,1498]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" value="2005.0">2005</number>
: 
<number id="305D24F8FFF16345C49F68E4B7DED68C" box="[1194,1241,1472,1498]" pageId="5" pageNumber="24" value="302.0">302</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
in rejoicing the preservation of “the only spider name which can be attributed to Charles Darwin.”
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
